issues.body:
LXNM allows to add static routes to the VPN.  The new requirement is to add support for adding BFD configuration in the IPv4 and IPv6 static routes.


Proposal below:

grouping bfd-static-routes {
    container bfd {
     description
       "Container for Static Routes BFD Configuration.";
     leaf bfd-session-name {
     type string;
       description
         "Specifies the name of a BFD session to associate and track.";
      }
      leaf desired-min-tx-interval {
        type uint32;
        units "miliseconds";
        default "1000";
        description
          "The minimum interval between
           transmissions of BFD Control packets, as
           desired by the operator.";
         reference
           "RFC 5880: Bidirectional Forwarding
            Detection (BFD), Section 6.8.7";
        }

       leaf required-min-rx-interval {
         type uint32;
           units "miliseconds";
           default "1000";
           description
             "The minimum interval between received BFD 
              Control packets that the PE should support.";
           reference
             "RFC 5880: Bidirectional Forwarding
              Detection (BFD), Section 6.8.7";
          }

       leaf local-multiplier {
         type uint8 {
           range "1..255";
         }
         default "3";
         description
           "Specifies the detection multiplier that
           is transmitted to a BFD peer.
           The detection interval for the receiving
           BFD peer is calculated by multiplying the
           value of the negotiated transmission
           interval by the received detection
           multiplier value.";
        reference
          "RFC 5880: Bidirectional Forwarding
           Detection (BFD), Section 6.8.7";
         }
  }
}


Below example on how to solve it with augmentation (in the bis this would go in the model)

augment "/l3vpn-ntw:l3vpn-ntw/l3vpn-ntw:vpn-services/l3vpn-ntw:vpn-service/l3vpn-ntw:vpn-nodes"
          + "/l3vpn-ntw:vpn-node/l3vpn-ntw:vpn-network-accesses/l3vpn-ntw:vpn-network-access/l3vpn-ntw:routing-protocols"
          + "/l3vpn-ntw:routing-protocol/l3vpn-ntw:static/l3vpn-ntw:cascaded-lan-prefixes/l3vpn-ntw:ipv4-lan-prefixes" {
        uses bfd-static-routes;
    }

	augment "/l3vpn-ntw:l3vpn-ntw/l3vpn-ntw:vpn-services/l3vpn-ntw:vpn-service/l3vpn-ntw:vpn-nodes"
          + "/l3vpn-ntw:vpn-node/l3vpn-ntw:vpn-network-accesses/l3vpn-ntw:vpn-network-access/l3vpn-ntw:routing-protocols"
          + "/l3vpn-ntw:routing-protocol/l3vpn-ntw:static/l3vpn-ntw:cascaded-lan-prefixes/l3vpn-ntw:ipv6-lan-prefixes" {
        uses bfd-static-routes;

In the model, a RD must be always asigned via profile at service level. It is useful to be able to set a explicit RD directly at nodel level overriding the value of the profile. This way, a common profile can be used for the whole services for use cases where only RD changes per node. 

The path were the leaf would be added.
"/l2vpn-ntw:l2vpn-ntw/l2vpn-ntw:vpn-services/l2vpn-ntw:vpn-service/l2vpn-ntw:vpn-nodes/l2vpn-ntw:vpn-node/" 
+ "l2vpn-ntw:active-global-parameters-profiles/l2vpn-ntw:global-parameters-profile" {

	leaf rd {
          type rt-types:route-distinguisher;
          description
            "Indicates an RD value that is explicitly assigned.";
        }
  }

Dear L3NM Working Group Members,

I am writing to propose a modification to the peer-as leaf definition within our YANG models. Currently, the peer-as leaf is defined as:

leaf peer-as {
type inet:as-number;
mandatory true;
description
"Indicates the customer's ASN when
the customer requests BGP routing.";
}

While type inet:as-number is the standard and semantically correct choice for Autonomous System Numbers (ASNs), I propose introducing a union type for peer-as to allow for greater flexibility, specifically by including a string type alongside inet:as-number. This would accommodate certain operational or legacy requirements where ASNs might be represented in non-standard string formats.

The proposed modification would look like this:

leaf peer-as {
mandatory true;
description
"Indicates the customer's ASN when
the customer requests BGP routing.";
type union {
type inet:as-number; // Retain the standard ASN type
type string {
// Define a pattern that allows for specific string representations,
// e.g., asdot+ or other custom formats.
// Example pattern (this would need to be carefully refined):
pattern '[0-9]+.[0-9]+';
description "Allows for ASNs represented as strings, e.g., asdot+ format or other specific string notations.";
}
}
}

The rationale for this proposal is to provide a mechanism for:

Enhanced Flexibility: To support scenarios where ASNs are provided or consumed in specific string formats that might not be strictly conformant with inet:as-number's internal parsing or for custom/legacy system integrations.
Explicit String Representation: Even though inet:as-number handles both "asplain" (integer) and "asdot+" (e.g., 65000.100) notations, explicitly allowing a string type in the union can provide a clear distinction for systems that prefer to represent "asdot+" as a string or require other specific string patterns.

It is crucial to acknowledge the implications of including a string type. A broadly defined pattern, such as [0-9]+.[0-9]+, could inadvertently accept values that are syntactically valid strings but semantically invalid ASNs. For instance, a value like 64086.59905 would be accepted by this pattern, despite not being a valid ASN in standard "asplain" or "asdot+" formats. Therefore, if a string type is included, its pattern must be meticulously crafted to strictly validate against intended string representations (e.g., a precise regex for "asdot+" or other agreed-upon formats) to prevent the configuration of semantically incorrect data.

This approach aims to strike a balance between strict type enforcement and practical operational flexibility.

Thank you for your time and consideration.
